{"text": "thumb|Carved whalebone whistle dated 1821. 8&nbsp;cm long.\nthumb|Quillacinga clay whistle, c. 1250\u20131500 AD, at the Museum of Texas Tech University.\nWhistles made of bone or wood have been used for thousands of years. Whistles were used by the Ancient Greeks to keep the stroke of galley slaves. \nArchaeologists have found a terracotta whistle at the ruins of the ancient Greek city of Assos, most probably a child's toy placed in a child's grave as a burial gift.\nThe English used whistles during the Crusades to signal orders to archers. Bosun's whistles were also used in the Age of Sail aboard naval vessels to issue commands and salute dignitaries.", "embedding": [0.025036935, 0.024886543, -0.2024226, -0.0952998, 0.06497404, -0.0007771547, 0.015417327, -0.012543212, -0.012289564, 0.018851148, -0.06611813, 0.009060559, 0.038179494, 0.03051311, 0.016996937, -0.076546475, 0.022422686, -0.0004083058, 0.031559743, 0.014538781, -0.033880495, -0.03137405, 0.003122414, 0.0007879097, 0.028609524, -0.02069726, 0.016805781, 0.059225786, 0.010742584, -0.048112664, 0.01960174, -0.048340447, -0.026500784, 0.002069509, -0.022973014, -0.06537978, 0.0126392795, -0.04460488, 0.05358865, 0.010420327, 0.04782162, -0.0021568108, -0.0060807597, 0.020355076, 0.07116596, -0.03544158, 0.027374132, -0.015347222, 0.050012868, -0.008200784, 0.07061263, -0.08136566, -0.012489982, -0.024931615, 0.04011412, -0.02159104, -0.0029380913, -0.04772985, 0.027948562, -0.007623488, 0.015587924, 0.08005637, -0.0038881497, 0.06853178, 0.06623338, 0.011455846, -0.024273384, 0.0268201, 0.049898572, 0.029091118, 0.048907824, -0.06470551, 0.031117313, 0.014748577, -0.035897482, 0.0077130455, -0.05498082, -0.0017721466, -0.029799419, 0.049082663, 0.075140186, -0.04029875, 0.06869392, 0.017005173, 0.04468983, 0.0037330915, -0.03864344, -0.0025576584, -0.032827776, 0.06759067, -0.003071774, -0.023337847, 0.050714083, 0.027464002, -0.029362086, 0.048766952, -0.017899718, 0.02034262, -0.0019559385, 0